[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Sir Frederick Samuel Inglefield''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (29 April 1854 - 8 August 1921) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who went on to be [[Fourth Sea Lord]].

==Naval career==
Inglefield was appointed [[Fourth Sea Lord]] from 1904 and then took command of the 4th Cruiser Squadron in 1907.<ref name=jewel>[http://www.inglefield.net/History.html Inglefield Jewelry Collection]</ref> He was awarded the title of Grand Officer of the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]] in recognition of services rendered during the [[earthquake]] at [[Messina]] in [[Sicily]] in 1908.<ref>[http://www.northeastmedals.co.uk/britishguide/colonial/messina_earthquake_awards.htm Messina Earthquake Awards]</ref> He served in [[World War I]] as Admiral Commanding the Auxiliary Coastal Patrol Forces.<ref>[http://rsnr.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/55/3/425.full.pdf Sea lions, greasepaint and the U-boat threat: Admiralty scientists turn to the music hall in 1916] Royal Society, 2001</ref>

He was later a member of the Official Inquiry into the loss of the [[RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] which was torpedoed by a German [[U-boat]] and sank with the loss of 1,198 lives south off the [[Old Head of Kinsale]] in [[Ireland]] on the 7 May 1915.<ref>[http://www.lusitania.net/boardoftrade.html Board of Trade]</ref> He also developed the ''Inglefield clip'', a shackle, which is used by signalmen on warships to attach multiple signal flags to a [[halyard]].<ref name=jewel/> He retired in 1916.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=29621|supp=yes|startpage=5828
|date=13 June 1916|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref>

In retirement he was a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of [[Derbyshire]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=29928|supp=|startpage=1177|date=2 February 1917|accessdate=2010-11-13}}</ref>

==Family==
In 1903 he married Millicent Evelyn Cecilia Crompton; they had two sons.<ref>[http://www.jjhc.info/inglefieldmillicent1950.htm Millicent Evelyn Cecilia G Inglefield]</ref>

